Session 9¶

What is statsmodels?¶

  • A library for statistical modeling, implementing standard statistical models in Python using NumPy and SciPy
  • Includes:
    • Linear (regression) models of many forms
    • Descriptive statistics
    • Statistical tests
    • Time series analysis
    • and much more ...
  • Statsmodels homepage:
    • http://statsmodels.sourceforge.net/
  • Statsmodels support for time series:
    • http://statsmodels.sourceforge.net/stable/tsa.html
    • http://www.statsmodels.org/stable/statespace.html
  • Other Packages:
    • Arch: http://arch.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html#
    • Prophet: https://facebook.github.io/prophet/

Descriptive statistics¶

Functions

  • stattools.acovf() Autocovariance for 1D
  • stattools.acf() Autocorrelation function for 1d arrays.
  • stattools.pacf() Partial autocorrelation estimated
  • stattools.ccovf() crosscovariance for 1D
  • stattools.ccf() cross-correlation function for 1d
  • stattools.periodogram(X) Returns the periodogram for the natural frequency of X

Statistical tests¶

  • Ljung-Box test for zero autocorrelation
  • Unit root test for cointegration (Augmented Dickey-Fuller test)
  • Granger-causality
  • Whiteness (iid-ness) and normality

Functions

  • stattools.adfuller() - Augmented Dickey-Fuller unit root test
  • stattools.kpss()- Kwiatkowski-Phillips-Schmidt-Shin test for stationarity.
  • stattools.coint() - Test for no-cointegration of a univariate equation
  • stattools.bds() - Calculate the BDS test statistic for independence of a time series
  • stattools.q_stat() - Return’s Ljung-Box Q Statistic

Estimation¶

  • Exponential Smoothing
    • holtwinters.ExponentialSmoothing() - Holt Winter’s Exponential Smoothing
    • holtwinters.SimpleExpSmoothing() - Simple Exponential Smoothing wrapper(…)
    • holtwinters.Holt() - Holt’s Exponential Smoothing wrapper(…)
    • holtwinters.HoltWintersResults() - Holt Winter’s Exponential Smoothing Result
  • Univariate Autogressive Processes (AR)
    • ar_model.AR() - Autoregressive AR(p) model
    • ar_model.ARResults() - Class to hold results from fitting an AR model.
  • Autogressive Moving-Average Processes (ARMA) and Kalman Filter
    • arima_model.ARMA() - Autoregressive Moving Average ARMA(p,q) Model
    • arima_model.ARMAResults() - Class to hold results from fitting an ARMA model.
    • arima_model.ARIMA() - Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average ARIMA(p,d,q) Model
    • arima_model.ARIMAResults()
    • more in statsmodels.tsa.arima_process
  • Vector Autogressive Processes (VAR)
    • vector_ar.var_model.VAR() - Fit VAR(p) process and do lag order selection
    • vector_ar.var_model.VARResults() - Estimate VAR(p) process with fixed number of lags
    • vector_ar.dynamic.DynamicVAR() - Estimates time-varying vector autoregression (VAR(p)) using equation-by-equation least squares
    • more in statsmodels.tsa.vector_ar.var_model

Example I¶

  • Develop an ARIMA model to forecast sale / demand of tractor for next 3 years.
  • Dataset: The monthly sales figures (number of tractors sold) for the last 12 years
Source: http://ucanalytics.com/blogs/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/ARIMA-TimeSeries-Analysis-of-Tractor-Sales.html#Step-1:-Visualize-Tractor-Sales-data-as-time-series¶

# Perform Dickey-Fuller test:
# adfuller?

dftest = adfuller(sales_ts, autolag='AIC')
print('Results of Dickey-Fuller Test:')
print(dftest)
print('********************************************* \n')

def printadfuller(dftest):
    dfoutput = pd.Series(dftest[0:4], index=['Test Statistic', 'p-value', '#lags Used', 
                                             'Number of Observations Used'])
    for key, value in dftest[4].items():
        dfoutput['Critical Value (%s)'%key] = value
    print('Results of Dickey-Fuller Test: (clean display)')
    print(dfoutput)
    print('''\n
*** Note: 
p-value>0.05 ==> null hypothesis is accepted ==> Data is non-stationary
''')

printadfuller(dftest)

# Kwiatkowski-Phillips-Schmidt-Shin test for stationarity.
# kpss?
kpsstest = kpss(sales_ts, lags='auto')
print('Results of KPSS Test:')
print(kpsstest)
print('********************************************* \n')


#     kpss_stat (float) – The KPSS test statistic
#     p_value (float) – The p-value of the test. The p-value is interpolated from Table 1 in Kwiatkowski et al. (1992), and a boundary point is returned if the test statistic is outside the table of critical values, that is, if the p-value is outside the interval (0.01, 0.1).
#     lags (int) – The truncation lag parameter
#     crit (dict) – The critical values at 10%, 5%, 2.5% and 1%. Based on Kwiatkowski et al. (1992).
#     resstore ((optional) instance of ResultStore) – An instance of a dummy class with results attached as attributes

    
def printkpss(dftest):
    dfoutput = pd.Series(dftest[0:3], index=['Test Statistic', 'p-value', '#lags Used'])
    for key, value in dftest[3].items():
        dfoutput['Critical Value (%s)'%key] = value
    print('Results of KPSS Test: (clean display)')
    print(dfoutput)
    print('''\n
*** Note: 
p-value>0.05 ==> null hypothesis is accepted ==> Data is stationary
''')

printkpss(kpsstest)

Important Inferences

  • The tractor sales have been increasing without fail every year.
  • July and August are the peak months for tractor sales and the variance and the mean value in July and August are also much higher than any of the other months.
  • We can see a seasonal cycle of 12 months where the mean value of each month starts with a increasing trend in the beginning of the year and drops down towards the end of the year. We can see a seasonal effect with a cycle of 12 months.

# smt.statespace.SARIMAX?

best_aic = np.inf
best_pdq = None
best_seasonal_pdq = None
temp_model = None

warnings.filterwarnings("ignore") # specify to ignore warning messages

for param in pdq:
    for param_seasonal in seasonal_pdq:
        
        try:
            temp_model = smt.statespace.SARIMAX(sales_ts_log,
                                             order = param,
                                             seasonal_order = param_seasonal,
                                             enforce_stationarity=True,
                                             enforce_invertibility=True)
            results = temp_model.fit()

            print("SARIMAX{}x{}12 - AIC: {:.2f}".format(param, param_seasonal, results.aic))
            if results.aic < best_aic:
                best_aic = results.aic
                best_pdq = param
                best_seasonal_pdq = param_seasonal
        except:
            #print("Unexpected error:", sys.exc_info()[0])
            continue
print("Best SARIMAX{}x{}12 model - AIC: {:.2f}".format(best_pdq, best_seasonal_pdq, best_aic))

pred_dynamic = best_results.get_prediction(start=pd.to_datetime('2012-01-01'), dynamic=True, 
                                           full_results=True)

#Note:  The dynamic=True argument: a better representation of our true predictive power 
#can be obtained using dynamic forecasts. In this case, we only use information from the time 
#series up to a certain point, and after that, forecasts are generated using values from 
#previous forecasted time points.


#pred_dynamic.conf_int?
#pred_dynamic.predicted_mean?

# Extract the predicted and true values of our time series
sales_ts_forecasted_dynamic = pred_dynamic.predicted_mean

# Extract the cI
pred_dynamic_ci = np.power(10, pred_dynamic.conf_int())

# Extract Actual values
sales_ts_truth = sales_ts_log['2012-01-01':]

# Compute the mean square error of one-step ahead forecasts
mse = ((sales_ts_forecasted_dynamic - sales_ts_truth) ** 2).mean()
print('The Mean Squared Error of our forecasts is {}'.format(round(mse, 4)))

_ = plt.figure(figsize=(14, 8))
_ = axis = sales_ts['2005':].plot(label='Observed')
_ = np.power(10, sales_ts_forecasted_dynamic).plot(ax=axis, label='Dynamic Forecast', alpha=0.7)
_ = axis.fill_between(pred_dynamic_ci.index, pred_dynamic_ci.iloc[:, 0], 
                      pred_dynamic_ci.iloc[:, 1], 
                      color='k', alpha=.25)
_ = axis.fill_betweenx(axis.get_ylim(), pd.to_datetime('2012-01-01'), 
                       sales_ts.index[-1], alpha=.1, 
                       zorder=-1)
_ = axis.set_xlabel('Years')
_ = axis.set_ylabel('Tractor Sales')

_ = best_results.plot_diagnostics(lags=30, figsize=(14,8))
# plt.show()

# best_results.plot_diagnostics?


# Discussion
# 1) The KDE plot of the residuals on the top right is almost similar with the normal 
#distribution.

# 2) The qq-plot on the bottom left shows that the ordered distribution of residuals (blue dots) 
# follows the linear trend of the samples taken from a standard normal distribution 
# with N(0, 1). Again, this is a strong indication that the residuals are normally distributed.

# 3) The residuals over time (top left plot) don't display any obvious seasonality and appear to
# be white noise. This is confirmed by the autocorrelation (i.e. correlogram) plot on the 
# bottom right, which shows that the time series residuals have low correlation with lagged
# versions of itself.
